		<item>
		<title>2015 Tibet Festival Held in Japan</title>
		<link>http://tibet.net/2015/06/2015-tibet-festival-held-in-japan/</link>
		<comments>http://tibet.net/2015/06/2015-tibet-festival-held-in-japan/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Fri, 05 Jun 2015 09:40:35 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Tenzin Yangchen]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[News Flash]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://tibet.net/?p=75991</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[JAPAN: Tibet House, Japan &#8211; a cultural wing of the Liaison Office of His Holiness the Dalai Lama for Japan and East Asia, organised a month long Tibet Festival in Japan from 27 April to 27 May at five different &#8230; <a href="http://tibet.net/2015/06/2015-tibet-festival-held-in-japan/">Continued</a>]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div class="pf-content"><div id="attachment_75992" style="width: 550px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="http://tibet.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/3.png" class="jackbox cta_post_image" style="display:block" data-group="images" data-thumbnail="http://tibet.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/3.png" >
<img class="size-full wp-image-75992 img-responsive " src="http://tibet.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/3.png" alt="Tibetan monks making sand Mandela, Japan." /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Tibetan monks making sand Mandala at 2015 Tibet Festival, Japan.</p></div>
<p>JAPAN: Tibet House, Japan &#8211; a cultural wing of the Liaison Office of His Holiness the Dalai Lama for Japan and East Asia, organised a month long Tibet Festival in Japan from 27 April to 27 May at five different prefectures in Japan namely Tokyo, Sapporo, Nagano, Sendai and Kouchi.</p>
<p>The objective of the festival is to enhance knowledge of Tibetan Buddhist culture and its way of life to the interested Japanese people. Eleven monks from Tashi Lhunpo monastery based in South India were invited for the festival.</p>
<p>The events of the festival were focused mainly on Tibetan Buddhist culture and its way of life. The highlights of the festival include making and explanation of sand mandala, spiritual dance (cham), teachings and meditation. Tibetan handicraft items, books on His Holiness and Tibet, T-shirt bearing Tibet symbol were sold as souvenirs. Many people have turned up and there was lot of enthusiasm among the audience. Some of them requested to organise such events frequently as it helps to boost their interest in understanding the Buddhism.</p>
<p>“We had the opportunity to educate the audience about the 11th Panchen Lama, the founder of Tashi Lhunpo monastery, and the current situation of the monastery in Tibet and India. A photo exhibition on the Panchen Lama was organised at Zenkoji temple in Nagano,” an official of the Liaison Office in Tokyo said.</p>
<p>The month-long Tibet Festival concluded on 28th May. The festival was organised with support from Shineiji Temple (Sapporo), Kichijoji Temple (Tokyo), Tibet Support Group Sendai (Sendai Prefecture), Saihoji Temple (Nagano Prefecture) and Joufukuji temple (Kouchi Prefecture).</p>
<div id="attachment_75993" style="width: 550px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="http://tibet.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/2.png" class="jackbox cta_post_image" style="display:block" data-group="images" data-thumbnail="http://tibet.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/2.png" >
<img class="size-full wp-image-75993 img-responsive " src="http://tibet.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/2.png" alt="Performance of Cham at Tibet festival in Japan." /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Performance of Tibetan spiritual dance, Cham at 2015 Tibet festival in Japan.</p></div>
</div>]]></content:encoded>
			<wfw:commentRss>http://tibet.net/2015/06/2015-tibet-festival-held-in-japan/feed/</wfw:commentRss>
		<slash:comments>0</slash:comments>
		</item>
